Great dish! For a potluck at our pottery studio, we served rice along with fresh cilantro, jalenpeno peppers and scallions! I didn't add any choco. and it tasted good. Also, I put everything in a crock pot when it was time to add the beans. Delish!

Rating: 3
Important note: I made HALF this recipe and it fed SIX hungry people with leftovers. Otherwise it was a nice change from the usual chili recipe. Rather than serving chocolate shavings as a garnish, I added 2 squares of "noir de noir" and produced a rich, velvety, molé-like sauce. Served with saffron rice, sour cream mixed with a cup of fresh, finely chopped cilantro and corn bread. Final note: don't have fake espresso so used a small cup of the real thing.

Rating: 4
This is a really unique-tasting chili. My batch turned out a little bitter, but I think it was because I used 1/3 cup ground Nicaraguan coffee instead of the espresso powder. (I also added 1/2 cup of semi-sweet chocolate chips when I added the beans). The flavors are rich and smokey, with just a hint of sweetness. I won the "most original" prize at an office chili cook off, and it really stood out from the more traditional offerings. I also wondered if maybe adding some green pepper or jalapeno (or ancho chiles?) might be worth doing...Good stuff for a cold day, and definitely for the adventurous at heart.

Rating: 3
Another winning chili recipe. Made it for just the two of us so I cut the recipe in half, added 1 1/2 tsp. coca powder. It was so thick I didn't really have to cook it down. In fact, when I went to heat it up for dinner (made it earlier in the day), it was so thick that I needed to add liquid...what else, but a little beer. Served it over white rice (beans and rice make a complete protein) and garnished it with non fat yogurt, sliced green onions and crushed lime flavored tortila chips. Hubby couldn.t stop saying "This is wonderful"

Rating: 4
My vegetable-conscious kids (ages 19 and 13) loved this, not only as chili but as filling for wraps/burritos. Like any bean dish, it gets better as it sits . . . but it won't be around for long at our house! I used good strong coffee in place of the espresso powder and water. Will be making this for our neighborhood chili cookoff next month!

